SIMPLE: intonate
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intonate
<hw>In"to*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>intonatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>intonare</ets> to thunder,
resound.]</ety> <def>To thunder.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bailey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intonate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Intonate
<hw>In"to*nate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Intonated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Intonating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See
<er>Intone</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To sound the tones of the musical
scale; to practice the sol-fa.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To modulate the voice in a musical, sonorous, and
measured manner, as in reading the liturgy; to intone.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intonate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Intonate
<hw>In"to*nate</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To utter in a musical or
sonorous manner; to chant; <as>as, to <ex>intonate</ex> the
liturgy</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intonation</ent>⟦br⟧
